  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nNote upfront: this is a pure Python backend (async fetchers + SQLite + CLI), no React/frontend code exists anywhere in the repo, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply — I've substituted the closest relevant category (redundant per-item computation) instead.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55–74) — **High impact**\n\nEvery fetched job does its own round-trip `SELECT`, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With `sources.yaml` configured for Microsoft (`max_pages=40`→~400 jobs), Amazon (~400), Netflix (~300), etc., a single run can push 1,000+ jobs through this loop — that's 1,000+ separate statement prepares/executes instead of a handful of batched calls.\n\n```python\n# store.py — before\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    elif row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash:\n        changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n```\n\nFix: one bulk `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` to build a lookup dict, then batch writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 bound-var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        ph = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(\n            (r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in\n            cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({ph})\", chunk)\n        )\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    inserts, updates = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title,\n            url, location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n            content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,\n            :content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\", inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type,\n            posted_at=:posted_at, salary_range=:salary_range,\n            content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900) reads + 3 batched writes.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation per job — `filters.py` (filters.py:11–12, 21–27) — **High impact**\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** driven by `filter_jobs`. For every one of ~1,000+ fetched jobs, every include/exclude keyword gets re-compiled into a fresh `re.Pattern` from scratch — pure wasted CPU, since the keyword lists are constant for the whole run.\n\n```python\n# filters.py — before: recompiles patterns on every call to match()\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job!\n            return False\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # same here\n            return False\n```\n\nFix — compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l.lower() in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if max_age := rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### 3. SQLite tuning: missing index + no WAL — **Medium impact**\n\n`added_since()` (store.py:127–135) filters/orders on `first_seen`, but the only index is on `company` — every `db-new` call full-scans the table. Also, `[[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]]` from prior context notes concurrent pipeline runs already collide on scratchpad/report paths; the default rollback-journal mode makes concurrent readers/writers block each other more than necessary.\n\n```python\n_SCHEMA = \"\"\"\n...\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_company ON jobs(company);\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n...\n\"\"\"\n\nclass Store:\n    def __init__(self, path: str | Path = \"jobs.db\"):\n        self.conn = sqlite3.connect(str(path))\n        self.conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row\n        self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")\n        self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA synchronous=NORMAL\")\n        self.conn.executescript(_SCHEMA)\n        ...\n```\n\nTable is currently small (~360KB db file) so this isn't urgent today, but it's cheap insurance as job history accumulates and matches the existing multi-worker usage pattern.\n\n### 4. Sequential pagination \"waterfalls\" in fetchers.py — **Low/situational**\n\nAmazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Google, Two Sigma, and Optiver fetchers all paginate with a strictly sequential `for page_n in range(max_pages): await ...` loop — each page waits for the previous one to fully round-trip before firing the next request, even though several of these APIs (Amazon, Workday) return a `total` count in the *first* response.\n\nThis is a real latency cost (Microsoft/Amazon can page up to 40 times per run), but I'd flag it as lower priority than #1–#3: parallelizing it risks tripping rate limits/anti-bot detection on the bespoke reverse-engineered endpoints (Google, Meta) that this codebase already treats carefully (per `[[meta-careers-fetcher]]` memory — doc_id rotation, token scraping). If you do want it, the safe version is: fetch page 1, read `total`, then fire remaining pages concurrently *only* for the APIs with clean documented JSON endpoints (Amazon, Workday) behind the existing `asyncio.Semaphore`, leaving the bespoke scrapers (Google, Meta, D.E. Shaw, Two Sigma) sequential.\n\n### Memory leaks — none found\n\nThis is a short-lived CLI process (fetch → filter → diff → notify → exit), not a long-running server, so classic leak patterns don't really apply. Resource lifecycles checked clean:\n- `Store` is always used via `with ... as store:` (pipeline.py:42, agent.py `_store()` call sites) — connections close properly, including on exceptions.\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:767–788) is closed in a `finally` block when the function owns it.\n- The Chrome subprocess in `cmd_pdf_render` (agent.py:234–241) uses a bounded `timeout=120` and cleans up its temp file in `finally`.\n\n### Caching — mostly not applicable\n\nThe whole point of each run is to detect *changes* in job postings, so caching the fetch responses would work against the tool's purpose. One legitimate, low-priority idea: several ATS JSON endpoints (Greenhouse, Lever, Ashby, SmartRecruiters) support conditional GET (`If-None-Match`/`ETag`); storing the last ETag per source in the existing `meta` table and sending `If-None-Match` would let unchanged boards return `304` instead of re-downloading the full payload — worth it only if bandwidth/rate-limit pressure becomes a real problem, not before.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order to fix:** #2 (filters.py regex, trivial fix, biggest CPU win per job) → #1 (store.py N+1, trivial fix, biggest win as job volume grows) → #3 (SQLite pragmas/index, 3-line change) → #4 (pagination concurrency, only if latency becomes a real complaint).\n\nWant me to implement #1 and #2 now? They're small, low-risk, and don't require any behavior/API changes.\n",
